[src:ecs-architecture/cache-prefetching] Cache prefetching can either fetch data or instructions into cache.
[src:ecs-architecture/cache-prefetching] Cache prefetching can be accomplished either by hardware or by software.
[src:ecs-architecture/cache-prefetching] This type of prefetching monitors the delta between the addresses of the memory accesses and looks for patterns within it.
[src:ecs-architecture/cache-prefetching] In this pattern, consecutive memory accesses are made to blocks that are *s* addresses apart.
[src:ecs-architecture/cache-prefetching] In this case, the prefetcher calculates the *s* and uses it to compute the memory address for prefetching.
[src:ecs-architecture/cache-prefetching] For example, if *s* = 4, the address to be prefetched would *A*+4.
[src:ecs-architecture/cache-prefetching] In this case, the delta between the addresses of consecutive memory accesses is variable but still follows a pattern.
[src:ecs-architecture/cache-prefetching] Some prefetcher designs exploit this property to predict and prefetch for future accesses.
[src:ecs-architecture/cache-prefetching] This class of prefetchers looks for memory access streams that repeat over time.
[src:ecs-architecture/cache-prefetching] For example, in the stream of memory accesses N, A, B, C, E, G, H, A, B, C, I, J, K, A, B, C, L, M, N, O, A, B, C, ...; the stream A, B, C is repeating over time.
[src:ecs-architecture/cache-prefetching] Other design variations have tried to provide more efficient implementations.
[src:ecs-architecture/cache-prefetching] Computer applications generate a variety of access patterns.
[src:ecs-architecture/cache-prefetching] The processor and memory subsystem architectures used to execute these applications further disambiguate the memory access patterns they generate.
[src:ecs-architecture/cache-prefetching] Hence, the effectiveness and efficiency of prefetching schemes often depends on the application and the architectures used to execute them.
[src:ecs-architecture/cache-prefetching] Recent research has focused on building collaborative mechanisms to synergistically use multiple prefetching schemes for better prefetching coverage and accuracy.
[src:ecs-architecture/cache-prefetching] Compiler-directed prefetching is widely used within loops with a large number of iterations.
[src:ecs-architecture/cache-prefetching] In this technique, the compiler predicts future cache misses and inserts a prefetch instruction based on the miss penalty and execution time of the instructions.
[src:ecs-architecture/cache-prefetching] These prefetches are non-blocking memory operations; that is, these memory accesses do not interfere with actual memory accesses.
[src:ecs-architecture/cache-prefetching] They do not change the state of the processor or cause page faults.
[src:ecs-architecture/cache-prefetching] One main advantage of software prefetching is that it reduces the number of compulsory cache misses.
[src:ecs-architecture/cache-prefetching] The following example shows the addition of a prefetch instruction into code to improve cache performance.
[src:ecs-architecture/cache-prefetching] the `i`th element of the array `array1` is accessed.
[src:ecs-architecture/cache-prefetching] Here, the prefetch stride, `k` depends on two factors, the cache miss penalty and the time it takes to execute a single iteration of the for-loop.
[src:ecs-architecture/cache-prefetching] For instance, if one iteration of the loop takes 7 cycles to execute, and the cache miss penalty is 49 cycles, then there should be k = 49/7 = 7 – which means that the system should prefetch 7 elements ahead.
[src:ecs-architecture/cache-prefetching] With the first iteration, `i` will be 0, so the system prefetches the 7th element.
[src:ecs-architecture/cache-prefetching] Now, with this arrangement, the first 7 accesses (`i` = 0 → 6) will still be misses (under the simplifying assumption that each element of `array1` is in a separate cache line of its own).
[src:ecs-architecture/cache-prefetching] Cache prefetching may be judged by three main metrics.
[src:ecs-architecture/cache-prefetching] Coverage is the fraction of total misses that are eliminated because of prefetching, i.e.
[src:ecs-architecture/cache-prefetching] Total Cache Misses = (Cache misses eliminated by prefetching) + (Cache misses not eliminated by prefetching).
[src:ecs-architecture/cache-prefetching] Accuracy is the fraction of total prefetches that were useful – that is, the ratio of the number of memory addresses prefetched that were actually referenced by the program to the total prefetches done.
[src:ecs-architecture/cache-prefetching] While it appears that having perfect accuracy might imply that there are no misses, this is not the case.
[src:ecs-architecture/cache-prefetching] The prefetches themselves might result in new misses if the prefetched blocks are placed directly into the cache.
[src:ecs-architecture/cache-prefetching] Although these may be a small fraction of the total number of misses observed without any prefetching, this is a non-zero number of misses.
[src:ecs-architecture/cache-prefetching] The qualitative definition of timeliness is the amount of time elapsed from prefetch to the actual reference.
[src:ecs-architecture/cache-prefetching] For example: for prefetching to be useful in a for loop where each iteration takes three cycles to execute and the prefetch operation takes twelve cycles, the system must start the prefetch 12/3 = 4 iterations prior to its usage to maintain timeliness.
[src:ecs-architecture/component-based-software-engineering] To find the right level of component granularity, software architects have to continuously iterate their component designs with developers.
[src:ecs-architecture/component-based-software-engineering] Architects need to take into account user requirements, responsibilities, and architectural characteristics.
[src:ecs-architecture/component-based-software-engineering] CBSE grew out of earlier paradigms such as structured programming and object-oriented programming, but it places greater emphasis on building software by assembling and integrating pre-existing components.
[src:ecs-architecture/component-based-software-engineering] Unlike objects, which typically encapsulate both data and behavior, components are higher-level constructs that provide well-defined interfaces and can be deployed independently.
[src:ecs-architecture/component-based-software-engineering] Component orientation underlies many modern software frameworks and architectural styles, including service-oriented architecture (SOA), microservices, and widely used frontend frameworks such as React, Angular, and Vue.
[src:ecs-architecture/component-based-software-engineering] For large-scale systems developed by large teams, a disciplined culture and process is required to achieve the benefits of CBSE.
[src:ecs-architecture/component-based-software-engineering] Third-party components are often utilized in large systems, raising issues of integration, licensing, and software quality.
[src:ecs-architecture/component-based-software-engineering] The system can be designed visually with the Unified Modeling Language (UML).
[src:ecs-architecture/component-based-software-engineering] Each component is shown as a rectangle, and an interface is shown as a lollipop to indicate a provided interface and as a socket to indicate consumption of an interface.
[src:ecs-architecture/component-based-software-engineering] This graphical representation helps clarify the relationships and dependencies between components.
[src:ecs-architecture/component-based-software-engineering] Component-based usability testing is applied when components interact directly with the end user, ensuring both functionality and user experience are preserved when components are reused or replaced.
[src:ecs-architecture/data-oriented-design] In computing, **data-oriented design** is a program optimization approach motivated by efficient usage of the CPU cache, often used in video game development.
[src:ecs-architecture/data-oriented-design] The approach is to focus on the data layout, separating and sorting fields according to when they are needed, and to think about transformations of data.
[src:ecs-architecture/data-oriented-design] Proponents include Mike Acton, Scott Meyers, and Jonathan Blow.
[src:ecs-architecture/data-oriented-design] The parallel array (or structure of arrays) is the main example of data-oriented design.
[src:ecs-architecture/data-oriented-design] It is contrasted with the *array of structures* typical of object-oriented designs.
[src:ecs-architecture/data-oriented-design] The definition of data-oriented design as a programming paradigm can be seen as contentious as many believe that it can be used side by side with another paradigm, but due to the emphasis on data layout, it is also incompatible with most other paradigms.
[src:ecs-architecture/data-oriented-design] These methods became especially popular in the mid to late 2000s during the seventh generation of video game consoles that included the IBM PowerPC based PlayStation 3 (PS3) and Xbox 360 consoles.
[src:ecs-architecture/data-oriented-design] Historically, game consoles often have relatively weak central processing units (CPUs) compared to the top-of-line desktop computer counterparts.
[src:ecs-architecture/data-oriented-design] This is a design choice to devote more power and transistor budget to the graphics processing units (GPUs).
[src:ecs-architecture/data-oriented-design] For example, the 7th generation CPUs were not manufactured with modern out-of-order execution processors, but instead use in-order processors with high clock speeds and deep pipelines.
[src:ecs-architecture/data-oriented-design] In addition, most types of computing systems have main memory located hundreds of clock cycles away from the processing elements.
[src:ecs-architecture/data-oriented-design] Furthermore, as CPUs have become faster alongside a large increase in main memory capacity, there is massive data consumption that increases the likelihood of cache misses in the shared bus, otherwise known as Von Neumann bottlenecking.
[src:ecs-architecture/data-oriented-design] Consequently, locality of reference methods have been used to control performance, requiring improvement of memory access patterns to fix bottlenecking.
[src:ecs-architecture/data-oriented-design] Some of the software issues were also similar to those encountered on the Itanium, requiring loop unrolling for upfront scheduling.
[src:ecs-architecture/data-oriented-design] The claim is that traditional object-oriented programming (OOP) design principles result in poor data locality, more so if runtime polymorphism (dynamic dispatch) is used (which is especially problematic on some processors).
[src:ecs-architecture/data-oriented-design] Although OOP appears to "organise code around data", it actually organises source code around data types rather than physically grouping individual fields and arrays in an efficient format for access by specific functions.
[src:ecs-architecture/data-oriented-design] Moreover, it often hides layout details under abstraction layers, while a data-oriented programmer wants to consider this first and foremost.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] ECS prioritizes composition over inheritance.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] Every entity is defined not by a type hierarchy, but by the components associated with it.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] Systems act globally over all entities that have the required components.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] For example, a food system might iterate through every entity with a relevant component tracking hunger, and act on them to push them a little away from satiation at time intervals.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] Entities lacking the component like terrain or items would be naturally ignored by the food system.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] Due to an ambiguity in the English language, an interpretation of the name is that an ECS is a system comprising entities and components.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] In the 2002 talk at GDC, Scott Bilas compared a C++ object system and his new custom component system.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] This is consistent with a traditional use of *system* terms in general systems engineering with Common Lisp Object System and type system as examples.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] Although mostly found in video game development, the ECS can be useful in other domains, such as in robotics simulators like Gazebo.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] ECS combines orthogonal, well-established ideas in general computer science and programming language theory.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] For example, components can be seen as a mixin idiom in various programming languages.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] Components are a specialized case under the general delegation approach and meta-object protocol.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] That is, any complete component object system can be expressed with the *templates* and *empathy* model within The Orlando Treaty vision of object-oriented programming.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] An entity represents a general-purpose object.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] In a game engine context, for example, every coarse game object is represented as an entity.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] Usually, it only consists of a unique ID.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] as possessing a particular aspect, and (the component) holds the data needed to model that aspect.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] For example, every game object that can take damage might have a Health component associated with its entity.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] A system is a process that acts on all entities with the desired components.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] For example, a physics system may query for entities having mass, velocity and position components, iterate over the results, and do physics calculations for each entity using the set of components.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] The behavior of an entity can be changed at runtime by systems that add, remove or modify components.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] This eliminates the ambiguity problems of deep and wide inheritance hierarchies often found in object-oriented programming techniques that are difficult to understand, maintain, and extend.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] Common ECS approaches are highly compatible with, and are often combined with, data-oriented design techniques.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] Data for all instances of a component are contiguously stored together in physical memory, enabling efficient memory access for systems that operate over many entities.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] In 1963, Ivan Sutherland's Sketchpad stored the visual elements of a drawing using an early form of an ECS.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] Instead of encapsulating points in different objects (e.g. lines, circles, rectangles) points were stored in a ring buffer, and visual elements were only referencing them.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] When moving a point, this allowed updating all the shapes and constraints using it.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] In 1998, *Thief: The Dark Project* pioneered an ECS.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] The engine was later used for its sequel, as well as *System Shock 2*.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] In 2002, Scott Bilas of Gas Powered Games (Dungeon Siege) gave a seminal talk on ECS.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] This inspired numerous later well-known implementations.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] In early January 2007, Mick West who worked on the Tony Hawk series, shared his experiences on the process of ECS adoption at Neversoft.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] Also in 2007, the team working on *Operation Flashpoint: Dragon Rising* experimented with ECS designs, including those inspired by Bilas/*Dungeon Siege*, and Adam Martin later wrote a detailed account of ECS design, including definitions of core terminology and concepts.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] In particular, Martin's work popularized the ideas of systems as a first-class element, entities as identifiers, components as raw data, and code stored in systems, not in components or entities.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] In 2015, Apple Inc. introduced GameplayKit, an API framework for iOS, macOS and tvOS game development that includes an implementation of ECS.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] In October 2018 the company Unity released its megacity demo that utilized a tech stack built on an ECS.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] Unity's ECS runs on a powerful optimized architecture known as DOTS, which "empowers creators to scale processing in a highly performant manner".
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] The data layout of different ECS's can differ as well as the definition of components, how they relate to entities, and how systems access entities' components.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] Adam Martin defines in his blog series what he considers an Entity–Component–System.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] An entity only consists of an ID for accessing components.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] It is a common practice to use a unique ID for each entity.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] Some of these advantages can also be achieved using smart pointers.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] Components have no game code (behavior) inside of them.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] The components don't have to be located physically together with the entity, but should be easy to find and access using the entity.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] Unity's layout has tables, each with columns of components.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] In this system an entity *type* is based on the components it holds.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] For every entity *type* there is a table (called an *archetype*) holding columns of components that match the components used in the entity.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] To access a particular entity one must find the correct archetype (table) and index into each column to get each corresponding component for that entity.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] The normal way to transmit data between systems is to store the data in components, and then have each system access the component sequentially.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] For example, the position of an object can be updated regularly.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] This position is then used by other systems.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] If there are a lot of different infrequent events, a lot of flags will be needed in one or more components.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] Systems will then have to monitor these flags every iteration, which can become inefficient.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] A solution could be to use the observer pattern.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] All systems that depend on an event subscribe to it.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] The action from the event will thus only be executed once, when it happens, and no polling is needed.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] The ECS has no trouble with dependency problems commonly found in object-oriented programming since components are simple data buckets and have no dependencies.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] Each system will typically query the set of components an entity must have for the system to operate on it.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] For example, a render system might register the model, transformations, and drawable components.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] When it runs, the system will perform its logic on any entity that has all of those components.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] Other entities are simply skipped, with no need for complex dependency trees.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] However, this can be a place for bugs to hide, since propagating values from one system to another through components may be hard to debug.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] ECS may be used where uncoupled data needs to be bound to a given lifetime.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] The ECS uses composition, rather than inheritance trees.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] An entity will be typically made up of an ID and a list of components that are attached to it.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] Any game object can be created by adding the correct components to an entity.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] This allows the developer to easily add features to an entity, without any dependency issues.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] For example, a player entity could have a *bullet* component added to it, which would then meet the requirements to be manipulated by some *bulletHandler* system, which then could result in that bullet doing damage to other objects by running into them.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] The merits of using ECS for storing the game state have been proclaimed by many game developers like Adam Martin.
[src:ecs-architecture/entity-component-system] One good example is the blog posts by Richard Lord, where he discusses the merits and why ECS-designed game data storage systems are so useful.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] In computer science, **locality of reference**, also known as the **principle of locality**, is the tendency of a processor to access the same set of memory locations repetitively over a short period of time.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] There are two basic types of reference locality – temporal and spatial locality.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] Temporal locality refers to the reuse of specific data and/or resources within a relatively small time duration.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] Spatial locality (also termed *data locality*) refers to the use of data elements within relatively close storage locations.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] Sequential locality, a special case of spatial locality, occurs when data elements are arranged and accessed linearly, such as traversing the elements in a one-dimensional array.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] Locality is a type of predictable behavior that occurs in computer systems.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] Systems which exhibit strong *locality of reference* are good candidates for performance optimization through the use of techniques such as the caching, prefetching for memory and advanced branch predictors of a processor core.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] When the matrix size is small, performance differences between traversal methods may appear minimal because the entire dataset fits inside the processor cache.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] However, as matrix dimensions increase, the access pattern becomes a critical factor, since non-sequential traversals generate significantly more cache misses and RAM accesses, reducing overall computational efficiency.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] In order to benefit from temporal and spatial locality, which occur frequently, most of the information storage systems are hierarchical.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] Equidistant locality is usually supported by a processor's diverse nontrivial increment instructions.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] For branch locality, contemporary processors have sophisticated branch predictors, and on the basis of this prediction the memory manager of the processor tries to collect and preprocess the data of plausible alternatives.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] These reasons are either goals to achieve or circumstances to accept, depending on the aspect.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] If most of the time the substantial portion of the references aggregate into clusters, and if the shape of this system of clusters can be well predicted, then it can be used for performance optimization.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] There are several ways to benefit from locality using optimization techniques.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] Hierarchical memory is a hardware optimization that takes the benefits of spatial and temporal locality and can be used on several levels of the memory hierarchy.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] Paging obviously benefits from temporal and spatial locality.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] A cache is a simple example of exploiting temporal locality, because it is a specially designed, faster but smaller memory area, generally used to keep recently referenced data and data near recently referenced data, which can lead to potential performance increases.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] Data elements in a cache do not necessarily correspond to data elements that are spatially close in the main memory; however, data elements are brought into cache one cache line at a time.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] This means that spatial locality is again important: if one element is referenced, a few neighboring elements will also be brought into cache.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] Finally, temporal locality plays a role on the lowest level, since results that are referenced very closely together can be kept in the machine registers.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] Some programming languages (such as C) allow the programmer to suggest that certain variables be kept in registers.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] Data locality is a typical memory reference feature of regular programs (though many irregular memory access patterns exist).
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] It makes the hierarchical memory layout profitable.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] In computers, memory is divided into a hierarchy in order to speed up data accesses.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] The lower levels of the memory hierarchy tend to be slower, but larger.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] Thus, a program will achieve greater performance if it uses memory while it is cached in the upper levels of the memory hierarchy and avoids bringing other data into the upper levels of the hierarchy that will displace data that will be used shortly in the future.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] This is an ideal, and sometimes cannot be achieved.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] Modern machines tend to read blocks of lower memory into the next level of the memory hierarchy.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] If this displaces used memory, the operating system tries to predict which data will be accessed least (or latest) and move it down the memory hierarchy.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] Prediction algorithms tend to be simple to reduce hardware complexity, though they are becoming somewhat more complicated.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] By switching the looping order for `j` and `k`, the speedup in large matrix multiplications becomes dramatic, at least for languages that put contiguous array elements in the last dimension.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] This will not change the mathematical result, but it improves efficiency.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] In this case, "large" means, approximately, more than 100,000 elements in each matrix, or enough addressable memory such that the matrices will not fit in L1 and L2 caches.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] The reason for this speedup is that in the first case, the reads of `A[i][k]` are in cache (since the `k` index is the contiguous, last dimension), but `B[k][j]` is not, so there is a cache miss penalty on `B[k][j]`.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] `C[i][j]` is irrelevant, because it can be hoisted out of the inner loop -- the loop variable there is `k`.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] In the second case, the reads and writes of `C[i][j]` are both in cache, the reads of `B[k][j]` are in cache, and the read of `A[i][k]` can be hoisted out of the inner loop.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] Thus, the second example has no cache miss penalty in the inner loop while the first example has a cache penalty.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] On a year 2014 processor, the second case is approximately five times faster than the first case, when written in C and compiled with `gcc -O3`.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] Temporal locality can also be improved in the above example by using a technique called blocking.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] The larger matrix can be divided into evenly sized sub-matrices, so that the smaller blocks can be referenced (multiplied) several times while in memory.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] Note that this example works for square matrices of dimensions SIZE x SIZE, but it can easily be extended for arbitrary matrices by substituting SIZE_I, SIZE_J and SIZE_K where appropriate.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] The temporal locality of the above solution is provided because a block can be used several times before moving on, so that it is moved in and out of memory less often.
[src:ecs-architecture/locality-of-reference] Spatial locality is improved because elements with consecutive memory addresses tend to be pulled up the memory hierarchy together.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] In computer science, **object composition** and **object aggregation** are closely related ways to combine objects or data types into more complex ones.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] In conversation, the distinction between composition and aggregation is often ignored.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] Common kinds of compositions are objects used in object-oriented programming, tagged unions, sets, sequences, and various graph structures.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] Object compositions relate to, but are not the same as, data structures.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] Object composition refers to the logical or conceptual structure of the information, not the implementation or physical data structure used to represent it.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] For example, a **sequence** differs from a **set** because (among other things) the order of the composed items matters for the former but not the latter.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] Data structures such as arrays, linked lists, hash tables, and many others can be used to implement either of them.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] Perhaps confusingly, some of the same terms are used for both data structures and composites.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] For example, "binary tree" can refer to either: as a data structure it is a means of accessing a linear sequence of items, and the actual positions of items in the tree are irrelevant (the tree can be internally rearranged however one likes, without changing its meaning).
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] However, as an object composition, the positions are relevant, and changing them would change the meaning (as for example in cladograms).
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] Object-oriented programming is based on using objects to encapsulate data and behavior.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] It uses two main techniques for assembling and composing functionality into more complex ones, sub-typing and object composition.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] Object composition is about combining objects within compound objects, and at the same time, ensuring the encapsulation of each object by using their well-defined interface without visibility of their internals.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] In this regard, object composition differs from data structures, which do not enforce encapsulation.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] Object composition may also be about a group of multiple related objects, such as a set or a sequence of objects.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] Delegation may enrich composition by forwarding requests or calls made to the enclosing composite object to one of its internal components.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] In class-based and typed programming languages, types can be divided into composite and non-composite types, and composition can be regarded as a relationship between types: an object of a composite type (e.g.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] *car*) "has" objects of other types (e.g.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] When a composite object contains several sub-objects of the same type, they may be assigned to particular roles, often distinguished by names or numbers.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] For example, a **Point** object might contain 3 numbers, each representing distance along a different axis, such as 'x', 'y', and 'z'.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] The study of part-whole relationships in general, is mereology.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] Composition must be distinguished from subtyping, which is the process of adding detail to a general data type to create a more specific data type.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] For instance, cars may be a specific type of vehicle: *car* is a *vehicle*.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] Subtyping doesn't describe a relationship between different objects, but instead, says that objects of a type are simultaneously objects of another type.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] The study of such relationships is ontology.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] In prototype-based programming languages such as JavaScript, objects can dynamically inherit the behaviors from a prototype object at the moment of their instantiation.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] Composition must be distinguished from prototyping: the newly instantiated object inherits the composition of its prototype, but it may itself be composed on its own.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] Composite objects may be represented in storage by co-locating the composed objects, by co-locating references, or in many other ways.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] The items within a composite object may be referred to as *attributes*, *fields*, *members*, *properties*, or other names, and the resulting composition as *composite type*, *storage record*, *structure*, *tuple*, or a *user-defined type (UDT)*.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] For details, see the aggregation section below.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] In UML modeling, objects can be conceptually composed, independently of the implementation with a programming language.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] The relationship between the aggregate and its components is a weak "has-a" relationship: The components may be part of several aggregates, may be accessed through other objects without going through the aggregate, and may outlive the aggregate object.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] The state of the component object still forms part of the aggregate object.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] Thus in UML, composition has a more narrow meaning than the usual object composition.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] Aggregation differs from ordinary composition in that it does not imply ownership.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] In composition, when the owning object is destroyed, so are the contained objects.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] In aggregation, this is not necessarily true.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] For example, a university owns various departments (e.g., chemistry), and each department has a number of professors.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] If the university closes, the departments will no longer exist, but the professors in those departments will continue to exist.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] Therefore, a university can be seen as a composition of departments, whereas departments have an aggregation of professors.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] In addition, a professor could work in more than one department, but a department could not be part of more than one university.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] Composition is usually implemented such that an object contains another object.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] In aggregation, the object may only contain a reference or pointer to the object (and not have lifetime responsibility for it).
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] Sometimes aggregation is referred to as composition when the distinction between ordinary composition and aggregation is unimportant.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] In Microsoft's Component Object Model, aggregation means that an object exports, as if it were their owner, one or several interfaces of another object it owns.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] Formally, this is more similar to composition or encapsulation than aggregation.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] However, instead of implementing the exported interfaces by calling the interfaces of the owned object, the interfaces of the owned object themselves are exported.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] The owned object is responsible for assuring that methods of those interfaces inherited from IUnknown actually invoke the corresponding methods of the owner.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] This is to guarantee that the reference count of the owner is correct and all interfaces of the owner are accessible through the exported interface, while no other (private) interfaces of the owned object are accessible.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] Composition that is used to store several instances of the composited data type is referred to as containment.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] Examples of such containers are arrays, associative arrays, binary trees, and linked lists.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] In UML, containment is depicted with a multiplicity of 0..* or 1..*, indicating that the composite object is composed of an unknown number of instances of the composed class.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] Objects can be composed recursively, and their type is then called recursive type.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] Examples includes various kinds of trees, DAGs, and graphs.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] Each node in a tree may be a branch or leaf; in other words, each node is a tree at the same time when it belongs to another tree.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] In UML, recursive composition is depicted with an association, aggregation or composition of a class with itself.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] The composite design pattern is an object-oriented design based on composite types, that combines recursive composition and containment to implement complex part-whole hierarchies.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] In this example, the primitive (non-composite) types `int`, `enum Employment` and the composite array type `char[]` are combined to form the composite structure `struct Person`.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] Each `struct Person` structure then "has an" age, name, and an employment type.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] C calls a record a struct or structure; object-oriented languages such as Java, Smalltalk, and C++ often keep their records hidden inside objects (class instances); languages in the ML family simply call them records.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] COBOL was the first widespread programming language to support records directly; ALGOL 68 got it from COBOL and Pascal got it, more or less indirectly, from ALGOL 68.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] Common Lisp provides structures and classes (the latter via the Common Lisp Object System).
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] Arrays were the only composite data type in Algol 60.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] For ALGOL 68 only the type name appears to the left of the equality, and most notably the construction is made – and can be read – from left to right without regard to priorities.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] Fortran 77 has arrays, but lacked any formal record/structure definitions.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] Ada 95 brought OOP concepts through tagged types (the equivalent of a C++ class), Ada 2012 added support for substitution verification through class-wide contracts.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] FORTRAN 90 updated and included FORTRAN IV's concept called `NAMELIST`.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] Common Lisp provides structures and the ANSI Common Lisp standard added `CLOS` classes.
[src:ecs-architecture/object-composition] For more details about composition in C/C++, see Composite type.
